{"questionId":"27835","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Stars are classified by their brightness. The brightest stars in the sky have a magnitude of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math>.&nbsp;The magnitude, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>m</mi></math>, of another star can be modelled as a function of its brightness, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi></math>, relative&nbsp;to a star of magnitude <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math>, as shown by the following equation.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>m</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo> </mo><msub><mi>log</mi><mn>10</mn></msub><mfenced><mi>b</mi></mfenced></math></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:left;\">The star called Acubens has a brightness of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0525</mn></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Find the magnitude of Acubens.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>m</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo> </mo><msub><mi>log</mi><mn>10</mn></msub><mfenced><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0525</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>20</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>19960</mn><mo>…</mo></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"27835","referenceCode":"22N.1.SL.TZ0.10a","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Find the magnitude of Acubens.","paper":"1","level":"SL","questionNumber":"a","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 1—Number and algebra","Topic 2—Functions","Topic 2—Functions","SL 2.6—Modelling skills","Topic 1—Number and algebra","SL 1.5—Intro to logs"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}